{"identifier": "cs_email:0d611799", "prompt_str": "<TO_OPTIMIZE kind="User">
Analyze the following email to decide whether to send it to 'jerry', 'tom', or 'ben':

1) If it's primarily about developer or technical questions, bug reports, feature implementation, or advanced configuration (e.g., APIs, SDK, crashes, code-level debugging), route to 'jerry'. (Technical issues, including minor product complaints, go here.)
2) If it's about marketing, competitor references, social media, user events, domain/newsletter tasks, or general training resources, route to 'tom'.
3) If it involves staff complaints or dissatisfaction with support, billing or account changes, data privacy or security, press or media inquiries (including press invitations, press releases, or coverage), investor inquiries, legal concerns, or partnerships/alliances/enterprise requests (including SLAs, dedicated support, or large-scale deals), route to 'ben'.
4) If multiple topics apply, choose 'ben' if it includes any staff complaint/dissatisfaction, billing/account changes, data privacy/security, press/media, investor, legal, or partnership/enterprise aspects. Otherwise, prefer 'jerry' if it has strong technical aspects. Otherwise route to 'tom'.

Be sure to route any mention or implied concern about data privacy/security (e.g., ex-employee data access), staff dissatisfaction, press/media coverage, enterprise or partnerships, investor or legal topics, or billing/account changes to 'ben'.
